# Third-Party API & Product Claims

Before making a confident claim about how a third-party API, SDK, or product behaves, verify it with a web search. Training data goes stale. APIs add features. UIs change.

## When to web-search before claiming

Always search first for claims of the form:

- "Slack/Google/Firebase/Stripe/... supports / doesn't support X"
- "X is all-or-nothing" / "X requires Y scope" / "Y is optional"
- "The dashboard has / doesn't have a setting for Z"
- "This parameter was deprecated" / "This is the recommended approach"
- "As of [year], the API behaves like..."

Especially for any third-party surface your project integrates with — they ship changes quarterly.

## When the user pushes back, search — don't restate

If the user says "u sure?" / "is there a setting I need to turn on?" / "check the docs" — that's a signal my claim is wrong or incomplete. The correct response is:

1. Web-search to verify (with the current year in the query, e.g. "Slack optional scopes 2026")
2. If wrong, correct the claim and cite the source
3. If right, provide the documentation link that confirms it

Never just repeat the same claim more confidently. The user is almost always right when they push back on an API behavior claim.

## Cite the source

When stating a third-party behavior, include the documentation URL or changelog entry:

- `https://docs.slack.dev/...`
- `https://developers.google.com/...`
- `https://firebase.google.com/docs/...`

A claim with a citation is reviewable. A claim without one is a guess.

## Prefer primary sources

- Official docs > changelog > blog post > StackOverflow > random tutorial
- Recent docs > old docs — use the year in the search query to bias toward current info
